{"title_page": "Master Harold...and the Boys (2010 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name         = Master Harold... and the Boys\n| image        = Lg_masterharold.jpg \n| caption      = Promotional poster\n| runtime      = 87 minutes\n| director     = [[Lonny Price]]\n| producer     = Michael Auret<br />Zaheer Goodman-Bhyat<br />David Pupkewitz<br />[[Morris Ruskin]]   \n| story        = [[Athol Fugard]] (play)\n| screenplay   = Nicky Rebello\n| starring     = [[Freddie Highmore]]<br />[[Ving Rhames]]<br />Patrick Mofokeng\n| cinematography = Lance Gewer\n| editing      = Ronelle Loots\n| music        = Philip Miller \n| budget       = $3 million\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| distributor  = [[Focus Films]]<br />Spier Films<br />[[Shoreline Entertainment]]\n| released     = {{Film date|2010|3|17|Cape Winelands}}\n}}\n'''''Master Harold...and the Boys''''' is a 2010 American [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] which is based on the original theatre [[\"Master Harold\"...and the Boys|play of the same name]] by [[Athol Fugard]], directed by director [[Lonny Price]].<ref name=HR>{{cite news | author =Stuart Kemp | title =Ving Rhames joins \"Master Harold\" | publisher =Hollywood Reporter/Reuters  | date =January 23, 2009 | url =https://www.reuters.com/article/filmNews/idUSTRE50M15V20090123 | accessdate=2009-04-06}}</ref>  The cast includes [[Freddie Highmore]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.filmmaker.co.za/readarticle.php?article_id=4221|title= Master Harold\u2026and the Boys starts shooting in Cape Town  |publisher=Filmmaker South Africa}}</ref> and [[Ving Rhames]].<ref name=HR /><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0700660/|title= Master Harold...and the Boys  | publisher= IMDB.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Master Harold...and the Boys\">{{cite web |url= http://www.shorelineentertainment.com/movies/MasterHarold.html|title= Master Harold...and the Boys |publisher=Shoreline Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|title= Fugard film shoots in Cape|publisher= SCREEN AFRICA|access-date= 2009-04-14|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111001085923/http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|archive-date= 2011-10-01|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allbusiness.com/humanities-social-science/visual-performing-arts/11767642-1.html|title= Ving Rhames joins 'Master Harold'|publisher=AllBusiness.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in Port Elizabeth, South Africa, during the early apartheid days. The story deals with the coming of age of seventeen-year-old Hally (played by [[Freddie Highmore]]). Hally, a white South African, has a bad relationship with his biological father and is torn between his father's expectations and opinions of him and those of his surrogate fathers, black waiters named Sam (played by [[Ving Rhames]]) and Willie (played by Patrick Mofokeng). Young Hally is obliged to laugh at his father's racist jokes and perform humiliating tasks like empty chamber pots. By contrast, Sam exposes Hally to many positive experiences. After being humiliated by his father, Sam shows Hally how to be proud of something he's achieved by helping him build and fly his own kite.<ref name=\"Master Harold...and the Boys\"/>\n\nOne day, Hally receives news that his real father, a violent alcoholic, is coming back home from a long stint in a hospital. Hally, distraught with this news, unleashes years of anger and pain on his two black friends.\n\n==Production==\nMaster Harold and the Boys began filming in and around Cape Town, South Africa in mid-January, 2009 over a five-week period. It is one of the first feature films in South Africa to be shot with the [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company#Recording media|red camera format]]. This film has a budget of just under $3m.<ref name=\"Fugard film shoots in Cape\">{{cite web|url= http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|title= Fugard film shoots in Cape|publisher= SCREEN AFRICA|access-date= 2009-04-14|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111001085923/http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|archive-date= 2011-10-01|url-status= dead}}</ref> Apart from its two international actors (Freddie Highmore & Ving Rhames), Nugent and American director Lonny Price, this film is a fully South African film.<ref name=\"Fugard film shoots in Cape\"/> Waterfront Post will post-produce this film, with Spier Films owning copyright. All the HOD's (Head of Department) are South African, including Director of Photography  Lance Gewer from the Oscar-winning Tsotsi, editor Ronelle Loots, production designer Tom Gubb and Pierre Viennings (wardrobe). Philip Miller is composing the music.\n\n==DVD / Blu-ray release==\nMaster Harold and the Boys was released in the United States on July 5, 2011 to DVD and Blu-ray.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.shorelineentertainment.com/movies/MasterHarold.html}}\n*{{IMDb title|1234546|Master Harold..and the Boys}}\n\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010 drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Africa]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name         = Master Harold... and the Boys\n| image        = Lg_masterharold.jpg \n| caption      = Promotional poster\n| runtime      = 87 minutes\n| director     = [[Lonny Price]]\n| producer     = Michael Auret<br />Zaheer Goodman-Bhyat<br />David Pupkewitz<br />[[Morris Ruskin]]   \n| story        = [[Athol Fugard]] (play)\n| screenplay   = Nicky Rebello\n| starring     = [[Freddie Highmore]]<br />[[Ving Rhames]]<br />Patrick Mofokeng\n| cinematography = Lance Gewer\n| editing      = Ronelle Loots\n| music        = Philip Miller \n| budget       = $3 million\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| distributor  = [[Focus Films]]<br />Spier Films<br />[[Shoreline Entertainment]]\n| released     = {{Film date|2010|3|17|Cape Winelands}}\n}}\n'''''Master Harold...and the Boys''''' is a 2010 film, which is based on the original theatre [[\"Master Harold\"...and the Boys|play of the same name]] by [[Athol Fugard]], directed by director [[Lonny Price]].<ref name=HR>{{cite news | author =Stuart Kemp | title =Ving Rhames joins \"Master Harold\" | publisher =Hollywood Reporter/Reuters  | date =January 23, 2009 | url =https://www.reuters.com/article/filmNews/idUSTRE50M15V20090123 | accessdate=2009-04-06}}</ref>  The cast includes [[Freddie Highmore]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.filmmaker.co.za/readarticle.php?article_id=4221|title= Master Harold\u2026and the Boys starts shooting in Cape Town  |publisher=Filmmaker South Africa}}</ref> and [[Ving Rhames]].<ref name=HR /><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0700660/|title= Master Harold...and the Boys  | publisher= IMDB.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Master Harold...and the Boys\">{{cite web |url= http://www.shorelineentertainment.com/movies/MasterHarold.html|title= Master Harold...and the Boys |publisher=Shoreline Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|title= Fugard film shoots in Cape|publisher= SCREEN AFRICA|access-date= 2009-04-14|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111001085923/http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|archive-date= 2011-10-01|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allbusiness.com/humanities-social-science/visual-performing-arts/11767642-1.html|title= Ving Rhames joins 'Master Harold'|publisher=AllBusiness.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in Port Elizabeth, South Africa, during the early apartheid days. The story deals with the coming of age of seventeen-year-old Hally (played by [[Freddie Highmore]]). Hally, a white South African, has a bad relationship with his biological father and is torn between his father's expectations and opinions of him and those of his surrogate fathers, black waiters named Sam (played by [[Ving Rhames]]) and Willie (played by Patrick Mofokeng). Young Hally is obliged to laugh at his father's racist jokes and perform humiliating tasks like empty chamber pots. By contrast, Sam exposes Hally to many positive experiences. After being humiliated by his father, Sam shows Hally how to be proud of something he's achieved by helping him build and fly his own kite.<ref name=\"Master Harold...and the Boys\"/>\n\nOne day, Hally receives news that his real father, a violent alcoholic, is coming back home from a long stint in a hospital. Hally, distraught with this news, unleashes years of anger and pain on his two black friends.\n\n==Production==\nMaster Harold and the Boys began filming in and around Cape Town, South Africa in mid-January, 2009 over a five-week period. It is one of the first feature films in South Africa to be shot with the [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company#Recording media|red camera format]]. This film has a budget of just under $3m.<ref name=\"Fugard film shoots in Cape\">{{cite web|url= http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|title= Fugard film shoots in Cape|publisher= SCREEN AFRICA|access-date= 2009-04-14|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111001085923/http://www.screenafrica.com/latest_edition/941854.htm|archive-date= 2011-10-01|url-status= dead}}</ref> Apart from its two international actors (Freddie Highmore & Ving Rhames), Nugent and American director Lonny Price, this film is a fully South African film.<ref name=\"Fugard film shoots in Cape\"/> Waterfront Post will post-produce this film, with Spier Films owning copyright. All the HOD's (Head of Department) are South African, including Director of Photography  Lance Gewer from the Oscar-winning Tsotsi, editor Ronelle Loots, production designer Tom Gubb and Pierre Viennings (wardrobe). Philip Miller is composing the music.\n\n==DVD / Blu-ray release==\nMaster Harold and the Boys was released in the United States on July 5, 2011 to DVD and Blu-ray.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.shorelineentertainment.com/movies/MasterHarold.html}}\n*{{IMDb title|1234546|Master Harold..and the Boys}}\n\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010 drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Africa]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Master_Harold...and_the_Boys_(2010_film)"}
{"title_page": "Mann Center for the Performing Arts", "text_new": "{{primarysources|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Venue |\n| name = Mann Center for The Performing Arts\n|  image        = [[File:Mann Center for the Performing Arts, June 2012.jpg|250px]]\n|  location     = 5201 Parkside Avenue <br>[[Fairmount Park]], [[Philadelphia]]\n|  opened       = 1976 \n|  owner        = City of [[Philadelphia]] \n|  former_names =  Mann Music Center (1976-2000)\n|  seating_capacity = 14,000 total, 4,743 under cover<ref>http://www.manncenter.org/about/mission-and-history</ref>\n|  website = http://www.manncenter.org/\n}}\nThe '''Mann Center for the Performing Arts''' (formerly known as the '''Mann Music Center''') is a nonprofit performing arts center located in the [[Centennial District, Philadelphia|Centennial District]] of [[Philadelphia]]'s West [[Fairmount Park]], built in 1976 as the summer home for the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]]. It is the successor in this role to the [[Robin Hood Dell]], where the Philadelphians have given summer performances since 1935. It has since hosted artists and touring companies such as the [[American Ballet Theatre]] with [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]], [[Marian Anderson]], [[Leonard Bernstein]], [[Buena Vista Social Club]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Judy Garland]], the [[Metropolitan Opera]], [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]], [[Paul Robeson]], [[Itzhak Perlman]], [[Lang Lang]], [[Midori (band)|Midori]], and [[Yo-Yo Ma]]. Major Philadelphia premieres have included the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[Bolshoi Ballet]] and Orchestra\u2019s production of Spartacus, and Britain\u2019s [[Royal Ballet]]\u2019s productions of Romeo and Juliet and Swan Lake. Among the scores of award-winning popular artists presented by the Mann in recent years are [[Jack Johnson (musician)|Jack Johnson]], [[Ed Sheeran]], [[Phish]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Roger Daltrey]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]], [[Arcade Fire]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Norah Jones]], [[Diana Krall]], [[Wynton Marsalis]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Smokey Robinson]], [[Jill Scott]], [[James Taylor]], [[Damien Rice]], [[Alabama Shakes]], [[Bon Iver]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[The National (band)|The National]], [[Steve Martin]], [[Martin Short]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]] with [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]], [[Sugarland]] and [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]].  In 2010, 2011 & 2014, the Mann was nominated by [[Pollstar]], a concert industry trade publication, as \"Best Major Outdoor Concert Venue\" in North America. The venue has a total [[seating capacity]] of approximately 14,000, with 4,743 seats under the roof and over 8,600 outside.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mann Center For The Performing Arts \u2013 History |url=http://www.manncenter.org/about/history.asp |publisher=Mann Center For The Performing Arts |accessdate=2008-05-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519172720/http://www.manncenter.org/about/history.asp |archivedate=2008-05-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe present building first opened in 1976 and subsequently was designated the Mann Music Center in honor of [[Fredric R. Mann]]. In 2000, the facility was renamed to The Mann Center for the Performing Arts to reflect the Center\u2019s plans to broaden its programming and service to the overall community.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mann Center For The Performing Arts \u2013 History|url=http://www.manncenter.org/about/history.asp|publisher=Mann Center For The Performing Arts|accessdate=2008-05-29 |archiveurl = http://manncenter.org/about/mission-and-history <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-05-19}}</ref>\n\n== Education and community engagement ==\nThe Mann Center for the Performing Arts\u2019 Education & Community Engagement program is the region\u2019s largest free education program, serving over 50,000 young people annually. The Mann\u2019s annual Young People\u2019s Concert Series features five free main stage performances making performing arts programs accessible to children in the Philadelphia region. The Connecting Arts-N-Schools series brings guest artists directly into 22 partner schools, and the Judith Gitlin ArtsTeach @ The Mann programs include 6 individual series: Meet the Artist, Tiny Tots Fascination Series, Greenfield Performance Treasures, Connecting Arts @ The Center, Artist in Residency and Master Class.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of contemporary amphitheatres]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://manncenter.org/ Mann Center's Official Website]\n*[https://plus.google.com/+themanncenter Mann Center's Official Website]\n*Map: {{Coord|39|58|59|N|75|13|22|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-PA}}\n\n[[Category:Music venues in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:West Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Fairmount Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{primarysources|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Venue |\n| name = Mann Center for The Performing Arts\n|  image        = [[File:Mann Center for the Performing Arts, June 2012.jpg|250px]]\n|  location     = 5201 Parkside Avenue <br>[[Fairmount Park]], [[Philadelphia]]\n|  opened       = 1976 \n|  owner        = City of [[Philadelphia]] \n|  former_names =  Mann Music Center (1976-2000)\n|  seating_capacity = 14,000 total, 4,743 under cover<ref>http://www.manncenter.org/about/mission-and-history</ref>\n|  website = http://www.manncenter.org/\n}}\nThe '''Mann Center for the Performing Arts''' (formerly known as the '''Mann Music Center''') is a nonprofit performing arts center located in the [[Centennial District, Philadelphia|Centennial District]] of [[Philadelphia]]'s West [[Fairmount Park]], built in 1976 as the summer home for the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]]. It is the successor in this role to the [[Robin Hood Dell]], where the Philadelphians have given summer performances since 1935. It has since hosted artists and touring companies such as the [[American Ballet Theatre]] with [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]], [[Marian Anderson]], [[Leonard Bernstein]], [[Buena Vista Social Club]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Judy Garland]], the [[Metropolitan Opera]], [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]], [[Paul Robeson]], [[Itzhak Perlman]], [[Lang Lang]], [[Midori (band)|Midori]], and [[Yo-Yo Ma]]. Major Philadelphia premieres have included the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[Bolshoi Ballet]] and Orchestra\u2019s production of Spartacus, and Britain\u2019s [[Royal Ballet]]\u2019s productions of Romeo and Juliet and Swan Lake. Among the scores of award-winning popular artists presented by the Mann in recent years are [[Jack Johnson (musician)|Jack Johnson]], [[Ed Sheeran]], [[Phish]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Roger Daltrey]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]], [[Arcade Fire]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Norah Jones]], [[Diana Krall]], [[Wynton Marsalis]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Smokey Robinson]], [[Jill Scott]], [[James Taylor]], [[Damien Rice]], [[Alabama Shakes]], [[Bon Iver]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[The National (band)|The National]], [[Steve Martin]], [[Martin Short]] and [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]].  In 2010, 2011 & 2014, the Mann was nominated by [[Pollstar]], a concert industry trade publication, as \"Best Major Outdoor Concert Venue\" in North America. The venue has a total [[seating capacity]] of approximately 14,000, with 4,743 seats under the roof and over 8,600 outside.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mann Center For The Performing Arts \u2013 History |url=http://www.manncenter.org/about/history.asp |publisher=Mann Center For The Performing Arts |accessdate=2008-05-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519172720/http://www.manncenter.org/about/history.asp |archivedate=2008-05-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe present building first opened in 1976 and subsequently was designated the Mann Music Center in honor of [[Fredric R. Mann]]. In 2000, the facility was renamed to The Mann Center for the Performing Arts to reflect the Center\u2019s plans to broaden its programming and service to the overall community.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mann Center For The Performing Arts \u2013 History|url=http://www.manncenter.org/about/history.asp|publisher=Mann Center For The Performing Arts|accessdate=2008-05-29 |archiveurl = http://manncenter.org/about/mission-and-history <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-05-19}}</ref>\n\n== Education and community engagement ==\nThe Mann Center for the Performing Arts\u2019 Education & Community Engagement program is the region\u2019s largest free education program, serving over 50,000 young people annually. The Mann\u2019s annual Young People\u2019s Concert Series features five free main stage performances making performing arts programs accessible to children in the Philadelphia region. The Connecting Arts-N-Schools series brings guest artists directly into 22 partner schools, and the Judith Gitlin ArtsTeach @ The Mann programs include 6 individual series: Meet the Artist, Tiny Tots Fascination Series, Greenfield Performance Treasures, Connecting Arts @ The Center, Artist in Residency and Master Class.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of contemporary amphitheatres]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://manncenter.org/ Mann Center's Official Website]\n*[https://plus.google.com/+themanncenter Mann Center's Official Website]\n*Map: {{Coord|39|58|59|N|75|13|22|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-PA}}\n\n[[Category:Music venues in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:West Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Fairmount Park]]\n", "name_user": "Dannydannyy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added some notable performers to the list.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann_Center_for_the_Performing_Arts"}
{"title_page": "Carl Gustav", "text_new": "'''Carl Gustav''' refers to two Kings of Sweden:\n\n*[[Charles X Gustav of Sweden]] (1622\u20131660), King of Sweden\n*[[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] (born 1946), King of Sweden\n\n'''Carl Gustav''' can also refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==People==\n\n===Politicians and rulers===\n*[[Charles X Gustav of Sweden]] (1622\u20131660), King of Sweden\n*[[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] (born 1946), King of Sweden\n*[[Karl Gustav Abramsson]] (born 1947), Swedish politician\n*[[Carl Gustaf Ekman]] (1872\u20131945), Swedish politician\n*[[Carl Gustaf L\u00f6wenhielm]] (1790\u20131858), Swedish diplomat\n*[[Carl Gustaf Nordin]] (1749\u20131812), Swedish statesman, historian and ecclesiastic\n*[[Carl Gustaf Tessin]] (1695\u20131770), Swedish politician\n*[[Karl Gustaf Westman]] (1876\u20131944), Swedish historian and politician\n\n===Athletes===\n*[[Carl Gustaf Lewenhaupt]] (1884\u20131935), Swedish horse rider\n*[[Karl Gustaf Vinqvist]] (1883\u20131967), Swedish gymnast\n\n===Artists===\n*[[Carl Gustaf Hellqvist]] (1851\u20131890), Swedish painter\n*[[Carl Gustaf Pilo]] (1711\u20131793), Swedish painter\n*[[Carl Gustav Carus]] (1789\u20131869), German physiologist and painter<!--also listed as a scientist-->\n\n===Entertainers===\n*[[Carl-Gustaf Lindstedt]] (1921\u20131992), Swedish actor\n*[[Karl Gustav Ahlefeldt]] (1910\u20131985), Danish film actor\n\n===Medicine===\n*[[Carl Gustav Carus]] (1789\u20131869), German physiologist and painter<!--also listed as an artist-->\n*[[Karl Gustav Himly]] (1772\u20131837), German surgeon and optician\n*[[Carl Jung|Carl Gustav Jung]] (1875\u20131961), Swiss founder of analytical psychology\n\n===Military leaders===\n*[[Carl Gustaf Armfeldt]] (1666\u20131736), Swedish military commander\n*[[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]] (1867\u2013 1951), Finnish military commander and statesman\n*[[Carl Gustav Fleischer]] (1883\u20131942), Norwegian military commander\n*[[Carl Gustav Rehnski\u00f6ld]] (1651\u20131722), Swedish military commander\n*[[Carl Gustaf von Nieroth]] (died 1712), Swedish military commander\n*[[Carl Gustaf Wrangel]] (1613\u20131676), Swedish military commander\n*[[Karl Gustav von L\u00f6wenwolde]] (died 1735), Russian diplomat and military commander\n\n===Science and medicine===\n*[[Carl Gustaf Mosander]] (1797\u20131858), Swedish chemist\n*[[Carl-Gustaf Rossby]] (1898\u20131957), Swedish-American meteorologist \n*[[Carl Gustaf Thomson]] (1824\u20131899), Swedish entomologist\n*[[Carl Gustaf von Mannerheim]] (1797\u20131854), Finnish entomologist\n*[[Carl Gustav Witt]] (1866\u20131946), German astronomer\n\n===Other persons===\n*[[Carl Gustaf von Rosen]] (1909\u20131977), Swedish aviator\n*[[Carl Gustaf Wolff]] (1800\u20131868), Finnish shipowner and businessman\n*[[Karl Gustav Homeyer]] (1795\u20131874), German jurist\n*[[Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi]] (1804\u20131851), German mathematician\n\n==Weaponry==\n*[[Bofors Carl Gustaf]], a Swedish armaments company\n*[[Carl Gustaf recoilless rifle]], an anti-tank weapon\n*[[Carl Gustaf m/45]], a submachine gun\n\n{{disambiguation|hndis|given name}}\n", "text_old": "'''Carl Gustav''' refers to two Kings of Sweden:\n\n*[[Charles X Gustav of Sweden]] (1622\u20131660), King of Sweden\n*[[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] (born 1946), King of Sweden\n\n'''Carl Gustav''' can also refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==People==\n\n===Politicians and rulers===\n*[[Charles X Gustav of Sweden]] (1622\u20131660), King of Sweden\n*[[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] (born 1946), King of Sweden\n*[[Karl Gustav Abramsson]] (born 1947), Swedish politician\n*[[Carl Gustaf Ekman]] (1872\u20131945), Swedish politician\n*[[Carl Gustaf L\u00f6wenhielm]] (1790\u20131858), Swedish diplomat\n*[[Carl Gustaf Nordin]] (1749\u20131812), Swedish statesman, historian and ecclesiastic\n*[[Carl Gustaf Tessin]] (1695\u20131770), Swedish politician\n*[[Karl Gustaf Westman]] (1876\u20131944), Swedish historian and politician\n\n===Athletes===\n*[[Carl Gustaf Lewenhaup